, and Norwegian: topographic name for someone who lived in or by a small wood, from Middle English, Middle Low German, Danish, and Norwegian <i>holt</i>, or a habitational name from one of the many places called with this word. In England, the surname is widely distributed, but more common in Lancashire and Yorkshire than elsewhere."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Henry Del Holte was born about 1250, in Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Holte. He married Mrs. Henry Del Holte in 1319, in Birmingham, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1250–":"umbes 1250–Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1260–1322":"1260–1322","–Male":"Surnud","Abt 1250":"umbes 1250","<1319>":"1319","1322":"1322","1300":"1300","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","Of Birmingham,Warwick,England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","<Of Birmingham,Warwick,Eng>":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of Warwick,England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1250–":"noin 1250–Kuollut","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1260–Female":"1260–Kuollut","1300–Female":"1300–Kuollut","1260–1322":"1260–1322","–Male":"Kuollut","Abt 1250":"noin 1250","<1319>":"1319","1322":"1322","1300":"1300","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","Of Birmingham,Warwick,England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskun